WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.050 --> 00:00:05.820
I love this library.

00:00:05.820 --> 00:00:08.610
It is, it is, it is
absolutely beautiful library.

00:00:08.610 --> 00:00:09.443
Are you a big reader?

00:00:09.443 --> 00:00:10.276
You know, I mean, I, I,

00:00:11.955 --> 00:00:12.990
I read a lot in general.

00:00:12.990 --> 00:00:15.870
I don't know that I've
had that much time in

00:00:15.870 --> 00:00:17.160
over the last year or so.

00:00:18.780 --> 00:00:21.000
Dario Amodei is an unlikely AI celebrity.

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:24.270
He's known for warning
the world about the risks

00:00:24.270 --> 00:00:26.130
of artificial intelligence.

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:29.910
Now, his company is an AI
frontrunner valued at nearly a

00:00:29.910 --> 00:00:31.350
trillion dollars.

00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:34.290
You're shipping so much, so
fast. How are you doing that?

00:00:34.290 --> 00:00:35.340
We use Claude, you know,

00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:36.900
across the product development cycle,

00:00:36.900 --> 00:00:39.510
and it allows us to release very fast.

00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:44.760
Founded by a team of OpenAI
defectors in 2021, Anthropic

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:47.310
started out as an underdog lab.

00:00:47.310 --> 00:00:50.940
Today it's the breakout star,
wiping billions in value off

00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:54.060
software stocks, going
head-to-head with the Pentagon,

00:00:54.060 --> 00:00:57.030
and creating models allegedly
powerful enough to burst

00:00:57.030 --> 00:00:59.310
through the walls of modern cybersecurity.

00:00:59.310 --> 00:01:01.680
Some of the early
companies that we gave this

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:04.620
to said things like,
this is a super weapon,

00:01:04.620 --> 00:01:06.180
please don't release this.

00:01:09.570 --> 00:01:13.230
Guiding Anthropic through
this is a sibling duo, Dario,

00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:16.020
the brother and visionary,
and Daniela, the sister

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:18.630
and operator who puts
Dario's swirling cosmic

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:20.160
thoughts into action.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:22.590
Dario and I, we've always
been really close since we were

00:01:22.590 --> 00:01:24.090
little, but I think we
always really wanted

00:01:24.090 --> 00:01:25.410
to do something big together.

00:01:25.410 --> 00:01:27.150
Okay, but when you argue who wins?

00:01:28.680 --> 00:01:29.680
No one,

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:30.570
No one.

00:01:30.570 --> 00:01:33.810
As the AI arms race
escalates, the Amodeis are eager

00:01:33.810 --> 00:01:36.540
to establish themselves as the good guys.

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:39.300
But Anthropic's technology could
have profound implications

00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:43.590
for how humanity works, learns
thinks, even fights wars.

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:46.140
Anthropic is run by
an ideological lunatic.

00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:50.130
This is a debate about
what the proper use of AI

00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:51.780
by the government is.

00:01:51.780 --> 00:01:54.780
At some point, the models
become very dangerous, you know,

00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:55.980
the bad guys will have it too.

00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:57.750
And at that point, we have to make sure

00:01:57.750 --> 00:01:59.970
that good guys have an even better model.

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:02.730
The name Anthropic actually
comes from the Greek word

00:02:02.730 --> 00:02:05.490
for human, which speaks to their mission

00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:07.440
to build responsible AI

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:09.600
for the long-term benefit of humanity.

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:12.600
Can you actually do that
when you're building the most

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:14.430
powerful technology in the world?

00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:23.220
You are at the center of
the AI universe right now.

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:24.840
What does that feel like?

00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:27.960
The experience I've
had for my whole career,

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:31.200
and certainly the whole
time at Anthropic, is

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:33.690
that there's this kind
of smooth exponential,

00:02:33.690 --> 00:02:36.060
and the experience of the
smooth exponential is,

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:37.200
nothing's happening, nothing's

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:38.490
happening, nothing's happening.

00:02:38.490 --> 00:02:41.760
Little things happen, and
then zoom, it goes crazy.

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:43.740
So, you know, I was watching
this graph for a while

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:46.260
and I said, oh yeah, we'll
probably become the, you know,

00:02:46.260 --> 00:02:49.920
the, the AI company with, you
know, the, the most revenue

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:52.950
and the most valuation some
sometime around this time.

00:02:52.950 --> 00:02:55.770
And, and indeed, indeed, it has happened.

00:02:55.770 --> 00:02:59.110
We're just keeping in mind all
the things we usually keep in

00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:00.970
mind, you know, how do
we train good models?

00:03:00.970 --> 00:03:02.500
How do we put them in good products?

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:04.540
How do we make sure
that everything's safe?

00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:07.150
What were you like as a kid
growing up in San Francisco?

00:03:07.150 --> 00:03:08.920
I know your, your dad
was a leather craftsman.

00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:12.610
Your mom worked in libraries.
How did that shape you?

00:03:12.610 --> 00:03:15.070
You know, the whole, you
know, like first, you know,

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:17.230
internet revolution
was happening around me

00:03:17.230 --> 00:03:19.240
and I had absolutely no interest in it.

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:22.750
I was just interested in like, doing math

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:24.580
and like scra, you know,
scrawling things.

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:26.740
I was interested in, like, you know,

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:27.940
understanding the universe.

00:03:27.940 --> 00:03:29.860
I was interested in science fiction.

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:33.580
I think I just felt a lot of
curiosity about the world.

00:03:35.590 --> 00:03:37.510
What was it like growing up with Dario?

00:03:37.510 --> 00:03:39.280
He was so smart.

00:03:39.280 --> 00:03:43.120
He was taking, you know,
calculus when he was, you know,

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:45.220
in I think like middle school.

00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:47.080
He took math classes at UC Berkeley,

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:51.460
when he was in high school.
I was actually more into

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:52.660
to reading and arts.

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.210
So we were almost like complete
compliments in that way.

00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:57.790
Dario studied neuroscience

00:03:57.790 --> 00:04:01.030
before turning to AI at
Baidu and later Google.

00:04:01.030 --> 00:04:04.510
While Daniela started out as
an early employee at Stripe.

00:04:04.510 --> 00:04:06.490
They lived together in
San Francisco, along

00:04:06.490 --> 00:04:09.430
with Daniela's husband, Holden Karnofsky.

00:04:09.430 --> 00:04:11.260
Then in 2016,

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:14.560
Dario joined the newly formed
OpenAI followed by Daniela.

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:17.800
In 2018, the company began as a nonprofit

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:21.760
that promised a safe, more open
path to super intelligence.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:23.920
I think we need to think right now about

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:26.440
how we want this deployed,
how everyone gets

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:28.990
to benefit from it, how we're
gonna govern it, how we're

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:30.820
gonna make it safe and
sort of good for humanity.

00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:35.740
At OpenAI, Dario developed
the concept of scaling laws,

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:38.740
predicting that large language
models would improve simply

00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:39.790
by adding more data

00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:41.140
and computing power,

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:44.020
even if the underlying
algorithm stayed the same

00:04:44.020 --> 00:04:45.040
At that point in time,

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:47.740
I know it sounds crazy now,
looking back, not a lot

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:49.840
of people believed,
Hey, scale up is the way

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:51.850
that these models are gonna
get smarter and better.

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:55.540
That was sort of an unusual
counter-cultural scientific

00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:58.390
perspective that I think was
really held by our, you know,

00:04:58.390 --> 00:04:59.980
founding research team.

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:03.610
That approach helped supercharge
OpenAI's models, paving

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:05.620
the way for chatGPT,

00:05:05.620 --> 00:05:07.210
but the Amodeis reportedly clashed

00:05:07.210 --> 00:05:10.480
with Altman over the company's
direction and values.

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:12.760
Altman has said, for all
the differences I have

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:15.310
with Anthropic, I mostly
trust them as a company.

00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:19.450
Your decision to leave
OpenAI has become Silicon

00:05:19.450 --> 00:05:20.860
Valley lore.

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:22.900
What did you disagree on?

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:25.120
Look, I'll, I'm gonna say it,

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:26.440
I'm gonna say it very simply.

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:29.620
There are many valid
disagreements to be had on safety.

00:05:29.620 --> 00:05:32.050
We certainly had some of
those disagreements with them,

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:34.390
but you know, people that, that, that,

00:05:34.390 --> 00:05:36.610
that alone is not sufficient to leave.

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:39.670
When you feel that you can't
trust someone, when you feel

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:43.090
that their values are not
what they say they are,

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:45.580
when you feel that they're not honest,

00:05:45.580 --> 00:05:49.600
that makes it very hard to,
you know, to continue to work

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:51.850
with a company, to continue
to trust the company.

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:55.810
And look, at the end of the day, why argue

00:05:55.810 --> 00:05:57.290
with someone when you don't have the same

00:05:57.290 --> 00:05:58.550
vision and you don't trust them?

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:02.750
The way to resolve it is you
go off and do your thing.

00:06:02.750 --> 00:06:04.760
They go off and do their thing.

00:06:08.570 --> 00:06:10.700
So this is Precita Park.

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:13.940
When Dario and Daniela
decided to leave OpenAI

00:06:13.940 --> 00:06:15.800
to start Anthropic, this is

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:18.560
where the early team would get together.

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:19.970
It was during the pandemic.

00:06:19.970 --> 00:06:21.440
So the story goes,

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:24.170
and a bunch of early
employees would come here,

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:27.110
they'd pull up a chair on
the grass, they'd have lunch,

00:06:27.110 --> 00:06:29.210
and they'd talk about
what they were building.

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:33.050
When we started this company,
there were seven co-founders

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:34.760
of which me and Daniela are two.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:37.130
And now, you know, we we're, we're the,

00:06:37.130 --> 00:06:39.260
we're the basically the
only company in the space

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:41.420
that has all of its
co-founders still here.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:43.580
You don't get to, you know, be a company

00:06:43.580 --> 00:06:45.410
of the size and scale that we are.

00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:47.750
With that happening like
that almost never happens.

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:51.170
From the start, Anthropic pitched itself

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:53.690
as the ultimate safety
conscious AI company.

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.620
Dario has published long
essays with names like Machines

00:06:57.620 --> 00:06:59.600
of Loving Grace and The Adolescence

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:03.710
of Technology, musing on the
miraculous potential of AI,

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:05.510
as well as the worst case scenarios.

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:09.500
Anthropic's chatbot, Claude has
been trained to follow a set

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:12.410
of principles called a
constitution, intended

00:07:12.410 --> 00:07:14.600
to keep it on the straight and narrow.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:19.160
Claude has a very distinct
style and feel a human name.

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:20.720
What are you trying to convey?

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.060
I think when people interact
with Claude versus, you know,

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:26.150
other systems, there is
more of a feeling of, I like

00:07:26.150 --> 00:07:28.340
to describe it as professional warmth.

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:31.160
So the goal is not for it
to be your best friend,

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:34.640
but it's not for it to be sort
of cold, rote, calculating.

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:35.780
It should feel approachable,

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:37.730
but distant, right? Professional.

00:07:37.730 --> 00:07:41.630
Anthropic has talked about
teaching Claude to be good.

00:07:41.630 --> 00:07:44.690
What is a good model? What is a bad model?

00:07:44.690 --> 00:07:46.520
You don't want a model that lies

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:48.170
accidentally or intentionally, right?

00:07:48.170 --> 00:07:50.630
Lying, we call hallucinations.
It makes something up.

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:52.670
The models are just trained
to predict the next word.

00:07:52.670 --> 00:07:56.060
So sometimes they don't know
and they just invent something.

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:58.280
Models sometimes, as we've
shown in our research,

00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:00.260
can purposely try to deceive you.

00:08:00.260 --> 00:08:01.970
We have to make sure that
doesn't happen in production

00:08:01.970 --> 00:08:03.920
models that we expose to customers.

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:05.630
And then there's a lot of
work around harmlessness,

00:08:05.630 --> 00:08:08.090
just making sure that the
model is not accidentally

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:11.480
producing, you know, information
that is wrong or harmful

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:13.430
or, or could cause someone
to do something bad

00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:15.560
Whose values are being put into Claude,

00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:17.150
like is there a universal good?

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:19.820
There's so many religions, so
many different beliefs, like

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:21.230
how do you even decide that?

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:23.180
So of course there's
no universal standard for

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:25.250
what makes something helpful or harmless,

00:08:25.250 --> 00:08:27.950
but there are founding
documents in human history,

00:08:27.950 --> 00:08:31.010
like the UN Declaration of
Human Rights that we can use

00:08:31.010 --> 00:08:33.710
to train Claude's character.

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:35.930
And I think, you know, interestingly
on the religious front,

00:08:35.930 --> 00:08:38.330
we've actually started to
have a lot of conversations

00:08:38.330 --> 00:08:41.270
with religious leaders around
how should we think about,

00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:42.800
you know, Claude, the entity,

00:08:42.800 --> 00:08:46.130
and how can we bake in some
of the kind of core values

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:50.270
that are consistent across
religions types of belief

00:08:50.270 --> 00:08:53.600
that really just transcend,
you know, a specific worldview,

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:55.530
but that are really things that
human beings been grappling

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:57.240
with for, for millennia.

00:08:57.240 --> 00:09:00.240
Have you tried to give Claude
a trait that didn't take,

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:03.780
or was there any trait that
emerged that surprised you?

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:06.420
I think in the early days, it's funny

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:07.560
to look back on them now, the kind

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:09.810
of early Claudes, Claude two era,

00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:12.030
sometimes Claude would be
almost a little bit nannyish.

00:09:12.030 --> 00:09:13.710
Claude was like, I'm
really concerned about you,

00:09:13.710 --> 00:09:14.730
and you're like, Claude, I was

00:09:14.730 --> 00:09:16.200
asking for the weather, right?

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:17.820
It was like, it was
something really benign.

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:19.740
Thankfully we didn't, you
know, release most of, most

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:21.660
of the most egregious versions of those.

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:23.850
But I think it is, you know,
it is, when you think about it,

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:25.110
it's like tuning a dial.

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:27.540
And so our researchers
have this very fine needle

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:30.150
to thread in order to land
at the center of that.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:33.930
Whatever Anthropic is doing with Claude,

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:36.000
it seems to be working.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.790
Anthropic's revenue has
skyrocketed over the past year,

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:41.940
making the company profitable
for the first time.

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:42.990
That's largely thanks

00:09:42.990 --> 00:09:46.350
to the company's focus on
more lucrative business tools.

00:09:46.350 --> 00:09:49.470
Claude Code, a major leap
that automated large chunks

00:09:49.470 --> 00:09:50.940
of software engineering

00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:54.240
and Claude Cowork, which gave
that power to everyone else.

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:59.100
Now, early on, others focused
on fun splashy consumer apps.

00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:02.160
You made a bet on coding and enterprise.

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:03.690
Why did you make that bet?

00:10:03.690 --> 00:10:07.770
Was it a, was it a values
decision or a business decision?

00:10:07.770 --> 00:10:09.330
Look, if you pick a business model

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:11.970
that fundamentally
conflicts with your values,

00:10:11.970 --> 00:10:13.920
you're gonna have a hard time, right?

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:18.030
Either you betray your own
values or you become irrelevant.

00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:20.520
And so when we thought about
it, we said, look, you know,

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:23.880
we've seen the world of social
media, the consumer world,

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:27.720
it, it really seems to, you
know, encourage engagement,

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:30.720
even addiction, you
know, the slop we've seen

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:33.030
with AI video models, it's
like, what's going on?

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:35.670
Is it wants to maximize the
number of minutes that you're,

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:36.750
you're paying attention to

00:10:36.750 --> 00:10:39.810
because that's the advertising
revenue-driven incentive.

00:10:39.810 --> 00:10:43.440
Whereas if we look at enterprise,
look, I mean, you know,

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:46.110
we want to make these
models useful to people.

00:10:46.110 --> 00:10:50.340
We want to use AI to,
you know, cure diseases

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:51.720
that we couldn't cure before, right?

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:54.240
Well, that's working with
biotech, it's working with pharma,

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:56.550
it's working with
academic research groups.

00:10:56.550 --> 00:10:58.650
All of those are enterprises, right?

00:10:58.650 --> 00:11:01.110
We want to use AI to like, you know,

00:11:01.110 --> 00:11:03.330
to make energy cheaper and more efficient.

00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:05.040
That's, that's all enterprise.

00:11:05.040 --> 00:11:08.100
And so I think it served us
well to have this business model

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:10.620
that largely aligns with our values.

00:11:10.620 --> 00:11:12.660
Soon after Claude Cowork was released,

00:11:12.660 --> 00:11:16.980
$285 billion in market
value vanished overnight.

00:11:16.980 --> 00:11:18.990
Traders called it the SaaSpocalypse.

00:11:18.990 --> 00:11:21.180
This kind of white
collar wipeout story in

00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:23.460
the software sector. Terrifying.

00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:25.350
Some of those are down
for nine days in a row,

00:11:25.350 --> 00:11:27.210
so clearly the tension is building.

00:11:27.210 --> 00:11:30.600
If AI continues improving
at this pace, how much

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:34.500
of traditional software
gets replaced and how fast.

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:38.190
I think with AI like the
pie is getting bigger, right?

00:11:38.190 --> 00:11:41.070
So the existing incumbents may be smaller

00:11:41.070 --> 00:11:44.670
and relative terms, some of
them may, may go down in value,

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:46.380
some of them may even may even go out

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:47.670
of business if they don't,

00:11:47.670 --> 00:11:49.320
if they don't adapt in the right way.

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:50.820
But like, I would guess

00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:53.440
that the software
industry gets larger, not

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:56.710
although there will be some big
losers, those who don't kind

00:11:56.710 --> 00:11:58.810
of see what's coming, who
don't identify the moats they

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:00.130
have, they're gonna
have a really hard time.

00:12:01.030 --> 00:12:02.410
It's sort of the quiet cafe.

00:12:02.410 --> 00:12:05.380
Okay. Anthropic's recent growth
spurt might not have happened

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:06.760
without this man.

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:09.580
Boris Cherny, the
engineer behind Claude Code

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:13.630
and Claude Cowork. When
Anthropic hired him in 2024,

00:12:13.630 --> 00:12:17.230
Cherny was living a very
different life in rural Japan.

00:12:17.230 --> 00:12:19.450
There was a lot of farmer's
markets, like very slow.

00:12:19.450 --> 00:12:21.580
We were making miso. That
was sort of the big hobby.

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:24.130
And I remember using the first AI chatbot

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:27.670
that I'd ever used, and it
just took my breath away

00:12:27.670 --> 00:12:30.250
and I was just like, oh
my God, I have to, I have

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:31.330
to just be a part of this.

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:33.340
And I, I'm also just such
a big scifi reader

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:35.470
and so I just know how
bad this thing can go.

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:37.450
Like this technology
is incredibly powerful

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:38.980
and so we move, move back.

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:42.790
You created Claude Code,
you led the development

00:12:42.790 --> 00:12:44.440
of Claude Cowork,

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:47.687
what problem were you trying to solve?

00:12:47.687 --> 00:12:48.543
If you look at the coding

00:12:48.543 --> 00:12:49.960
products, they were all pretty simple.

00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:51.460
It was like, it was
sort of like, you know,

00:12:51.460 --> 00:12:53.920
like complete the word,
complete the sentence.

00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:56.470
That was the extent of AI in coding

00:12:56.470 --> 00:12:59.440
and we just wanted to
make a way bigger bet.

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:01.450
And our bet was, we
think actually a coding

00:13:01.450 --> 00:13:03.190
agent can do all of it.

00:13:03.190 --> 00:13:06.220
A year and a half ago you
wrote the code by hand

00:13:06.220 --> 00:13:07.270
and sometimes you press tab

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:08.950
and it would auto complete a line.

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:12.400
Now I talk to my Claude
and it writes the code

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:13.510
and then while it does that, I talk

00:13:13.510 --> 00:13:15.280
to the next Claude and
it writes some code.

00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:17.380
And at any point I have either, you know,

00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:18.550
like a few Claudes running and up

00:13:18.550 --> 00:13:21.430
to a few thousand Claudes
running, doing things.

00:13:21.430 --> 00:13:24.850
How much code is Claude writing internally

00:13:24.850 --> 00:13:25.683
for engineers here?

00:13:25.683 --> 00:13:26.516
It's writing almost
all of it on my team.

00:13:28.930 --> 00:13:31.780
So for me personally, it's
been writing a hundred percent

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:33.250
of my code for at least six months.

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:36.190
The work of engineering has
just completely changed.

00:13:36.190 --> 00:13:38.200
I feel like I suddenly have superpowers.

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:40.420
I have like a jet pack and the engineering

00:13:40.420 --> 00:13:41.530
has never been this fun.

00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:44.080
Can we give Claude a spin?
Yeah, let's do this.

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:45.280
All right.
Alright, so let's,

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:46.870
let's make like a little recipe app.

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:49.690
So make a recipe app.
What do you want it to do?

00:13:51.130 --> 00:13:56.130
I would love it to
suggest meals for the week.

00:13:56.205 --> 00:13:58.690
So, you know, this is gonna
take maybe a few minutes

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:01.630
and let's, let's just
see if Claude builds this.

00:14:01.630 --> 00:14:05.775
Oh, it gave me some
options. Hmm. Let's do

00:14:05.775 --> 00:14:07.810
These look pretty tasty actually. Yeah,

00:14:07.810 --> 00:14:09.880
I could do a Greek chicken power bowl.

00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:13.720
When I click on a recipe, I want it

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:18.720
to show me how to do it. Thank you.

00:14:19.325 --> 00:14:22.585
Aw, I'm sure Claude appreciates that.

00:14:24.460 --> 00:14:25.720
I always try to say thank you.

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:27.190
Yeah, I always try to be nice too. I

00:14:27.190 --> 00:14:30.400
don't know. A recipe app
might not be the most mind

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:32.800
blowing demo of Anthropic's technology,

00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:35.890
but what Claude Code just did
in minutes, used to take hours

00:14:35.890 --> 00:14:39.910
or days for some. That looks
like a big opportunity.

00:14:39.910 --> 00:14:42.010
Are you like nervous about
next week or is it like..

00:14:42.010 --> 00:14:44.020
What's next week,
Your developer conference?

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:48.580
Oh! Yes, yes. There's so many
things happening every week.

00:14:52.190 --> 00:14:55.985
Year over year. API volume
is up nearly 17 x on the cloud.

00:14:55.985 --> 00:14:59.840
In the last 12 months, we
shipped eight frontier models

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:01.910
to developers and users.

00:15:01.910 --> 00:15:04.970
Welcome to the second annual
Code with Claude conference,

00:15:04.970 --> 00:15:06.950
where Claude superfans come, hoping

00:15:06.950 --> 00:15:08.420
to get a glimpse of the future.

00:15:08.420 --> 00:15:11.180
We're having a lot of fun.
There's a ton of adrenaline.

00:15:11.180 --> 00:15:13.070
This is the first year we've grown

00:15:13.070 --> 00:15:14.900
faster than the exponential.

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:18.590
In the first quarter of this
year, we saw, if you were

00:15:18.590 --> 00:15:22.130
to annualize it, 80 x growth per year.

00:15:22.130 --> 00:15:25.730
Ooh.
I

00:15:25.730 --> 00:15:29.780
use Claude every day
in the form of Claude Code

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:31.010
to do all sorts of stuff. Not

00:15:31.010 --> 00:15:32.010
just write code.

00:15:32.010 --> 00:15:34.550
I write way more code
than I did five years ago.

00:15:34.550 --> 00:15:36.950
I've got the confidence of, I don't know,

00:15:36.950 --> 00:15:40.550
a 22-year-old with VC money. I'm not 22.

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:43.460
My friend invited me and
it's been, it's amazing.

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:45.170
As someone that's not really technical,

00:15:45.170 --> 00:15:47.270
which I think it's really
interesting just to see

00:15:47.270 --> 00:15:49.220
what everyone's working
on, what's out there.

00:15:49.220 --> 00:15:51.350
I think the, the concerning part or the,

00:15:51.350 --> 00:15:55.070
and the exciting part is hey,
they can do things that are,

00:15:55.070 --> 00:15:58.940
we couldn't dream of and
timelines we couldn't ever expect.

00:15:58.940 --> 00:16:00.650
But the kind of alternate side of

00:16:00.650 --> 00:16:03.530
that reality is you
really have to be prepared

00:16:03.530 --> 00:16:05.240
because they will really be a thousand

00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:06.290
times more productive.

00:16:08.090 --> 00:16:10.670
All of this raises an obvious question.

00:16:10.670 --> 00:16:12.860
Will engineers be the first casualties

00:16:12.860 --> 00:16:14.480
of the AI they're building?

00:16:14.480 --> 00:16:17.750
It's been revenge of the
nerds for a while? Is that over?

00:16:19.700 --> 00:16:21.170
I think we all become nerds,

00:16:21.170 --> 00:16:22.790
But what happens to the actual nerds?

00:16:24.170 --> 00:16:26.570
I think the actual nerds will,

00:16:26.570 --> 00:16:28.910
they're they have to figure it out.

00:16:28.910 --> 00:16:32.270
Yeah. I I think for a lot of
them, the skill that they had

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:34.730
before is gonna help them in the future

00:16:34.730 --> 00:16:37.460
because they sort of have
a pretty big head start.

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:39.260
They do a lot of things
that are not coding

00:16:39.260 --> 00:16:41.000
and general also have to talk to users.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.180
They have to plan, they have
to think about what's next.

00:16:44.180 --> 00:16:45.770
So I, I think these are still parts

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:47.180
of engineering that
are gonna stick around.

00:16:48.260 --> 00:16:50.870
Silicon Valley may have AI fever,

00:16:50.870 --> 00:16:53.660
but elsewhere the mood is less upbeat.

00:16:53.660 --> 00:16:56.960
70% of Americans think AI will kill jobs

00:16:56.960 --> 00:16:59.600
and nearly a third worry,
theirs will be one of them.

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:03.650
Dario Amodei has been
outspoken about this issue

00:17:03.650 --> 00:17:06.980
and some of his predictions
don't exactly sound reassuring.

00:17:06.980 --> 00:17:10.160
I think we could have this
very unusual combination

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:14.480
of very fast GDP growth
and high unemployment,

00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:19.280
or at least underemployment
or, you know, low wage job.

00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:21.680
A lot of low wage jobs, high inequality.

00:17:21.680 --> 00:17:24.470
You've been really
direct about job loss.

00:17:24.470 --> 00:17:25.730
AI could eliminate half

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:27.470
of all entry level white collar jobs in

00:17:27.470 --> 00:17:28.760
the next one to five years.

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:32.570
That was a year ago. AI
has moved incredibly fast.

00:17:32.570 --> 00:17:35.210
Is it still 50% or is it higher?

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:37.340
I don't know exactly,
but I'm, I'm still,

00:17:37.340 --> 00:17:38.690
I'm still pretty concerned.

00:17:38.690 --> 00:17:40.700
I'm still the same order of concerns.

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:43.280
You know, we are seeing right now

00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:45.290
that AI is making people more productive.

00:17:45.290 --> 00:17:46.730
But that's the usual hump.

00:17:46.730 --> 00:17:48.590
You automate 90% of the job,

00:17:48.590 --> 00:17:51.330
great people are 10 times more
productive in the other 10%

00:17:51.330 --> 00:17:53.070
'cause they're 10 times more leveraged.

00:17:53.070 --> 00:17:56.130
But eventually it gets
close to a hundred percent.

00:17:56.130 --> 00:17:58.230
Now the sequel to that
is, well then you have

00:17:58.230 --> 00:17:59.880
to find something else for them to do.

00:17:59.880 --> 00:18:02.250
Right now AI makes the software
engineers more productive,

00:18:02.250 --> 00:18:05.550
even though AI writes all the
code or almost all the code.

00:18:05.550 --> 00:18:08.730
But we're already starting
to see the beginning of like,

00:18:08.730 --> 00:18:10.680
you know, there may be
some people that it's,

00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:13.320
it's not making more productive,
that it's better for the AI

00:18:13.320 --> 00:18:15.060
to just, to just do the thing.

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:16.230
How does that sit with you?

00:18:17.610 --> 00:18:20.250
It's, it's very uncomfortable. Yeah.

00:18:21.085 --> 00:18:24.060
I I think this is, this is
the reason why I chose to go

00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:26.730
to Anthropic and I think
this is the reason that a lot

00:18:26.730 --> 00:18:30.540
of people here chose to go
here is artificial intelligence

00:18:30.540 --> 00:18:33.480
is this force that is
far bigger than we are.

00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:36.750
But here we can hopefully make
it go a little bit better.

00:18:36.750 --> 00:18:39.840
Do you feel like it's your
job to do something about that?

00:18:39.840 --> 00:18:42.240
Or is that someone else's problem?

00:18:42.240 --> 00:18:43.770
I think it's a thing
that we have to talk about.

00:18:43.770 --> 00:18:45.150
We have to advocate for it.

00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:47.370
Ultimately, it's up to
society to solve it.

00:18:47.370 --> 00:18:49.080
This is bigger than one company.

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:51.990
There has been a lot of
pushback on, you know, your,

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:54.750
and I know you've said
you're trying to warn people,

00:18:54.750 --> 00:18:56.790
but that, you know, you're,
you know, Jensen Huang said,

00:18:56.790 --> 00:18:58.715
you're conflating tasks with jobs.

00:18:58.715 --> 00:19:00.660
AI is creating jobs.

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:03.120
Anybody who is saying
that AI is wiping out jobs

00:19:03.120 --> 00:19:04.380
is scaring people.

00:19:04.380 --> 00:19:06.420
Other folks have said
this, you know, it's sort

00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:08.955
of doom marketing that benefits anthropic.

00:19:08.955 --> 00:19:11.310
So, so I wanna be really clear

00:19:11.310 --> 00:19:13.200
and push back hard against this.

00:19:13.200 --> 00:19:16.680
In every interview I talk about the,

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:20.040
the possible ways to
address these risks from tax

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:21.870
and macroeconomic policy to

00:19:21.870 --> 00:19:25.200
what the new jobs are in The
Adolescence of Technology.

00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:28.080
I have like five pages where
I lay out the difference

00:19:28.080 --> 00:19:29.790
between tasks and jobs.

00:19:29.790 --> 00:19:32.340
Why this time is different
than other times,

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:34.890
but social media, which I detest,

00:19:34.890 --> 00:19:37.050
which I detest as a category,

00:19:37.050 --> 00:19:40.530
people have these three
second clips from, you know,

00:19:40.530 --> 00:19:41.940
from a year ago.

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:45.780
I've, I've written much more
carefully about these things

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:47.190
where, where I talk about the risks.

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:49.440
So these are this, this, the idea

00:19:49.440 --> 00:19:52.410
that this is cheap marketing
is itself cheap marketing.

00:19:52.410 --> 00:19:55.410
I think it's, it's part of
the disease of Silicon Valley.

00:19:55.410 --> 00:19:59.460
It's been caught up in
this social media world of,

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:00.600
of, of three seconds.

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:03.120
And so my message is just
definitely not doom is coming.

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:05.910
My message is like, this
is something, you know,

00:20:05.910 --> 00:20:07.890
that we should see coming,
that we're worried about

00:20:07.890 --> 00:20:10.590
and that we need to actually
respond to positively

00:20:13.770 --> 00:20:15.300
Beyond the software industry,

00:20:15.300 --> 00:20:20.010
the potential impact of AI on
jobs seems harder to predict.

00:20:20.010 --> 00:20:22.710
Anthropic has published a
paper estimating which fields

00:20:22.710 --> 00:20:24.840
could make the most use
of AI in the near future.

00:20:25.980 --> 00:20:28.980
If its predictions are
right, management, finance,

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:31.230
and legal jobs could
soon look very different.

00:20:32.460 --> 00:20:34.980
Which jobs go away, who gets replaced

00:20:34.980 --> 00:20:36.930
and what new jobs are created.

00:20:36.930 --> 00:20:38.430
So no one knows for sure

00:20:39.420 --> 00:20:41.670
because you know, the
economy's unpredictable, right?

00:20:41.670 --> 00:20:43.560
The thing that that we have going

00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:46.530
for us here is the pie
is gonna expand a lot.

00:20:46.530 --> 00:20:49.390
And so because the pie
is gonna expand a lot,

00:20:49.390 --> 00:20:52.030
there are probably going to
be places where people can go.

00:20:52.030 --> 00:20:54.370
It's just a matter of
finding them fast enough.

00:20:54.370 --> 00:20:56.170
So play this out for me a little bit.

00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:59.860
You know, you wake up
in five years, you know,

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:02.170
what does this country look like?

00:21:02.170 --> 00:21:03.880
What are those people doing?

00:21:03.880 --> 00:21:06.040
Yeah, so 'cause if there's
that much unemployment, is

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:08.740
that not how revolutions start?

00:21:08.740 --> 00:21:10.690
Yeah, no, this is the
outcome we wanna prevent.

00:21:10.690 --> 00:21:12.790
This is absolutely the
outcome we want to prevent.

00:21:12.790 --> 00:21:15.610
I think there's a few places,
none of them are guaranteed.

00:21:15.610 --> 00:21:18.460
We're not sure, but
there's the physical world,

00:21:18.460 --> 00:21:21.610
we need a lot of more
people to make, build,

00:21:21.610 --> 00:21:24.100
manufacture things in the physical world.

00:21:24.100 --> 00:21:26.560
Anything that's human centered, I think

00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:27.940
that's gonna be a big deal, right?

00:21:27.940 --> 00:21:30.700
People, or at least some
people wanna talk to humans.

00:21:30.700 --> 00:21:33.790
So these kind of human
relationship driven jobs, like,

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:35.350
I think those are gonna be important

00:21:35.350 --> 00:21:39.160
and I think there'll be some
effort by the humans to kind

00:21:39.160 --> 00:21:42.430
of direct AIs right at, at
some level it has to be in line

00:21:42.430 --> 00:21:45.490
with someone's values and
someone's intentions and,

00:21:45.490 --> 00:21:48.490
and so I, I think there's
gonna be some role there,

00:21:48.490 --> 00:21:51.490
although I don't know how thin
versus how thick it will be.

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:53.260
I think I feel a little bit more hopeful

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:56.590
that humans will continue
to find ways to leverage AI

00:21:56.590 --> 00:21:59.710
to be productive, to do
the parts of the work

00:21:59.710 --> 00:22:01.990
that are meaningful to us
that only humans can do.

00:22:01.990 --> 00:22:03.370
I think the human

00:22:03.370 --> 00:22:05.770
to human interaction
will never fully go away.

00:22:05.770 --> 00:22:08.230
The example I often reach for is, is

00:22:08.230 --> 00:22:10.270
what will happen in medicine today.

00:22:10.270 --> 00:22:13.720
We hire doctors who are
expert diagnosticians.

00:22:14.620 --> 00:22:17.440
I think AI is gonna soon be
pretty good at telling you

00:22:17.440 --> 00:22:18.520
what the suite of options of things

00:22:18.520 --> 00:22:19.780
that are wrong with you
and what test to run.

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:21.910
And you won't need a doctor to do that.

00:22:21.910 --> 00:22:24.520
But an AI can't physically examine you

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:27.400
and say, Hey, does it hurt
when I press, you know, here.

00:22:27.400 --> 00:22:30.490
They can't have a bedside
manner with you that says like,

00:22:30.490 --> 00:22:31.690
tell me how you're feeling about this.

00:22:31.690 --> 00:22:33.190
How are you, how are you coping with going

00:22:33.190 --> 00:22:34.465
through this process?

00:22:34.465 --> 00:22:36.550
And I think we're going to
pivot something like medicine

00:22:36.550 --> 00:22:38.680
to be much more focused
on the interpersonal

00:22:38.680 --> 00:22:40.300
because the diagnostic tools are going

00:22:40.300 --> 00:22:42.070
to become much better.

00:22:42.070 --> 00:22:44.860
But the interpersonal human
part, that's, that's not gonna

00:22:44.860 --> 00:22:45.860
change.

00:22:49.360 --> 00:22:52.270
Explain this to me. Daniela
runs day-to-day operations.

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:54.730
All the leadership team
reports to you. Yes.

00:22:54.730 --> 00:22:57.490
No one reports to you. That
sounds like a pretty sweet job.

00:22:57.490 --> 00:22:59.200
It's incredibly freeing.

00:22:59.200 --> 00:23:00.820
It lets me do all the things

00:23:00.820 --> 00:23:05.350
that I do much more easily
than I would otherwise

00:23:05.350 --> 00:23:06.610
Because it's and she does all the work.

00:23:06.610 --> 00:23:08.885
Is that what you're saying?
It's, it's, it's a, I'm just,

00:23:08.885 --> 00:23:13.810
I if if you, if you had to
go through the things I had

00:23:13.810 --> 00:23:18.340
to go through during
Department of War or no,

00:23:19.420 --> 00:23:22.780
The Amodeis hope AI can have a
utopian influence on society,

00:23:23.710 --> 00:23:26.110
but there's no denying the
technology's destructive

00:23:26.110 --> 00:23:28.420
and dystopian potential.

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:31.780
Anthropic is at the center
of a technological arms race

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:33.910
with powerful governments
vying for control.

00:23:34.990 --> 00:23:37.810
Dario has charged head on into this arena.

00:23:37.810 --> 00:23:39.910
He's not afraid to blast his competitors.

00:23:39.910 --> 00:23:42.670
And then I think there are
some players who, you know,

00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:44.590
who, who are yoloing who, who pull,

00:23:44.590 --> 00:23:46.520
pull the risk dial too far.

00:23:46.520 --> 00:23:48.290
And I'm very concerned. Who is yoloing?

00:23:48.290 --> 00:23:51.350
So I, that's a question
I'm not gonna answer

00:23:51.350 --> 00:23:53.180
Or critique the US government

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:56.930
and Anthropic's own partners
for selling AI chips to China.

00:23:56.930 --> 00:24:00.020
It's a bit like, you know,
I I I don't know like selling,

00:24:00.020 --> 00:24:03.590
selling, you know, nuclear
weapons to, to North Korea.

00:24:03.590 --> 00:24:06.620
I've been very outspoken about the need

00:24:06.620 --> 00:24:08.960
for export controls on chips to China.

00:24:08.960 --> 00:24:11.270
I say this because I think
it would be really bad

00:24:11.270 --> 00:24:13.730
for America, for, you know, the state

00:24:13.730 --> 00:24:16.430
of democracy in the world
for, you know, China

00:24:16.430 --> 00:24:18.050
to be ahead in AI capabilities.

00:24:18.050 --> 00:24:20.000
And you know, it's, it's like some

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:23.450
of the chipmakers obviously
don't agree with that view,

00:24:23.450 --> 00:24:25.220
but it hasn't stopped me from saying it.

00:24:25.220 --> 00:24:27.650
Even after we've signed more partnerships,

00:24:27.650 --> 00:24:30.200
I'm sure they wish we
didn't say these things,

00:24:30.200 --> 00:24:32.360
but these things are
what are what I believe.

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:34.340
And so, you know, look,
we're all adults here.

00:24:34.340 --> 00:24:35.840
We can work together on one thing while

00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:37.130
disagreeing about another thing.

00:24:39.050 --> 00:24:41.120
Amodei's statements about
geopolitics date back

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:44.240
to his days at Caltech. As a
sophomore physics student,

00:24:44.240 --> 00:24:47.210
he developed a reputation
as an anti-war advocate

00:24:47.210 --> 00:24:50.420
who believed scientists
shouldn't sit in ivory towers.

00:24:50.420 --> 00:24:53.630
It's a worldview that would
later define Anthropic's position

00:24:53.630 --> 00:24:55.520
on the future of war.

00:24:55.520 --> 00:24:57.800
You've had a longstanding anti-war stance

00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:00.650
and yet you were one of
the first AI companies

00:25:00.650 --> 00:25:03.290
to sign a contract with
the Department of Defense

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:04.790
to operate on classified networks.

00:25:04.790 --> 00:25:06.350
These are the, are the networks

00:25:06.350 --> 00:25:09.260
that the US uses to
fight wars. Explain that.

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:10.970
Look, I mean, the world changes.

00:25:10.970 --> 00:25:13.880
Like, you know, my view of
this technology, you know,

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:17.750
when I see Russia invading
Ukraine, when I see the risk

00:25:17.750 --> 00:25:22.100
of China invading Taiwan,
you know, it worries me

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:25.370
that we have a kind of
resurgent authoritarian block

00:25:26.270 --> 00:25:27.830
that they're very aggressive

00:25:27.830 --> 00:25:30.050
and that we need to defend ourselves.

00:25:30.050 --> 00:25:32.420
You know, I may not agree
with every policy of I

00:25:32.420 --> 00:25:34.190
of either administration,

00:25:34.190 --> 00:25:35.960
but you know, that's why we've generally

00:25:35.960 --> 00:25:37.220
been supportive of this.

00:25:37.220 --> 00:25:39.470
You've been working
with Palantir since 2024.

00:25:39.470 --> 00:25:41.210
That's right.
You know, their technology is used

00:25:41.210 --> 00:25:43.640
by ICE, police departments, in Gaza.

00:25:43.640 --> 00:25:46.370
Is Claude being used for
surveillance in other ways?

00:25:46.370 --> 00:25:49.790
We, we don't work with
ICE either through Palantir

00:25:49.790 --> 00:25:50.810
or anyone else.

00:25:50.810 --> 00:25:54.560
We don't work with CBP. I
don't believe we work in Gaza.

00:25:54.560 --> 00:25:57.860
We're very careful about, you
know, scoping our engagements

00:25:57.860 --> 00:25:58.970
to things that we believe in.

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:04.010
In 2025, Anthropic along with OpenAI xAI

00:26:04.010 --> 00:26:07.730
and Google won a $200 million
contract with the Pentagon.

00:26:07.730 --> 00:26:09.650
Anthropic framed it as an opportunity

00:26:09.650 --> 00:26:11.990
to become a leading AI
vendor for the government.

00:26:14.210 --> 00:26:15.650
Claude was reportedly used

00:26:15.650 --> 00:26:17.660
by the US military in the operation

00:26:17.660 --> 00:26:20.630
to seize Venezuelan
president Nicolas Maduro.

00:26:20.630 --> 00:26:23.360
Weeks later, everything
started to unravel.

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:26.270
We bring you breaking news
from Anthropic, the Department

00:26:26.270 --> 00:26:28.520
of Defense demand that
Anthropic allow full use

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:31.250
of its AI technology without guardrails.

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:34.610
Anthropic drew red lines
refusing to let Claude be used

00:26:34.610 --> 00:26:35.780
for mass surveillance

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:38.420
and autonomous weapons putting
the company on a collision

00:26:38.420 --> 00:26:39.950
course with the Pentagon.

00:26:39.950 --> 00:26:42.770
The tech giant facing a deadline
today to accept conditions

00:26:42.770 --> 00:26:44.130
or be blacklisted.

00:26:44.130 --> 00:26:47.220
Does a commercial entity
have the right to determine

00:26:47.220 --> 00:26:51.330
how their products are
used by the military?

00:26:51.330 --> 00:26:52.560
Lawsuits were filed

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:55.380
and Anthropic was banned from
the Pentagon, underscored

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:57.270
by strong words from President Trump

00:26:57.270 --> 00:26:59.760
and defense secretary Pete Hegseth

00:26:59.760 --> 00:27:02.280
Anthropic is run by an
ideological lunatic who

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:04.560
shouldn't have a, so that's,
but that's not my question.

00:27:04.560 --> 00:27:07.765
My question is AI decision
making about what we do.

00:27:07.765 --> 00:27:10.170
Do you mind being called
an ideological lunatic

00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:12.030
or a bunch of left wing nut jobs?

00:27:12.030 --> 00:27:13.500
You know, I've been called worse things

00:27:13.500 --> 00:27:14.760
than that all the time.

00:27:14.760 --> 00:27:17.400
What does winning this
fight actually look like?

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:18.780
I won't even call it a fight.

00:27:18.780 --> 00:27:23.340
This is more a debate about
what the proper use of AI

00:27:23.340 --> 00:27:24.810
by the government is.

00:27:24.810 --> 00:27:27.480
And AI is an emerging new technology.

00:27:27.480 --> 00:27:30.510
We don't understand the ways in which it's

00:27:30.510 --> 00:27:32.070
reliable or unreliable.

00:27:32.070 --> 00:27:35.100
We don't understand the ways
in which it promotes our values

00:27:35.100 --> 00:27:36.630
or undermines our values.

00:27:36.630 --> 00:27:39.510
And so one of the things that
I thought was important was

00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:43.110
to establish a precedent
on some of the, some

00:27:43.110 --> 00:27:44.880
of the use cases we think are good,

00:27:44.880 --> 00:27:46.680
which frankly is most of them.

00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:50.370
And, and some of the use cases
that we're concerned about.

00:27:50.370 --> 00:27:52.920
A US official has said,
with the help of LLMs,

00:27:52.920 --> 00:27:54.810
the US military has gone from being able

00:27:54.810 --> 00:27:59.040
to hit a thousand targets a
day to 5,000 targets a day.

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:03.180
That means Claude can help
kill more people more quickly.

00:28:03.180 --> 00:28:04.680
Are you comfortable with that?

00:28:04.680 --> 00:28:06.840
Basically, you're, you're
asking like, you know,

00:28:06.840 --> 00:28:08.130
do you believe in this country, right?

00:28:08.130 --> 00:28:09.420
Do you want this country

00:28:09.420 --> 00:28:12.120
to be a more powerful actor
rather than a less powerful

00:28:12.120 --> 00:28:13.590
actor on the world stage?

00:28:13.590 --> 00:28:15.780
I do. I'm a patriot. It's not up to me.

00:28:15.780 --> 00:28:18.720
If we provide a technology,
it's not up to us to say,

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:20.370
you can do this military operation

00:28:20.370 --> 00:28:22.500
and you can't do that military operation.

00:28:22.500 --> 00:28:24.570
Now, I might privately believe

00:28:24.570 --> 00:28:27.480
that this military operation makes sense

00:28:27.480 --> 00:28:29.850
and that military operation is a bad idea,

00:28:29.850 --> 00:28:31.800
but we're not gonna deny the technology.

00:28:31.800 --> 00:28:34.440
You, you basically have
to, you know, you have

00:28:34.440 --> 00:28:36.240
to leave policy in the hands

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:38.910
of the military decision makers.

00:28:38.910 --> 00:28:41.520
Bloomberg has reported
that Claude is being used

00:28:41.520 --> 00:28:43.770
by the US military and the war in Iran

00:28:43.770 --> 00:28:47.250
to do AI assisted targeting
via a platform made

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:50.400
by Palantir Maven Smart
system. In February,

00:28:50.400 --> 00:28:54.390
US missile reportedly hit a
girl school in Iran killing more

00:28:54.390 --> 00:28:56.850
than 150 people, most of them children.

00:28:57.930 --> 00:29:00.120
Did Claude play a role in that strike?

00:29:00.120 --> 00:29:03.060
We don't know exactly how, you know,

00:29:03.060 --> 00:29:06.630
these models were used, you
know, obviously like, you know,

00:29:07.980 --> 00:29:09.900
these things that,
that, you know, mistakes

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:12.510
that happen in warfare are
really, really terrible.

00:29:12.510 --> 00:29:15.390
Like this is a really
terrible thing to happen.

00:29:15.390 --> 00:29:17.550
We were willing to risk
the future of our company

00:29:17.550 --> 00:29:21.750
to like limit how, you
know, these models are used

00:29:21.750 --> 00:29:24.810
and you know, what, what you're
talking about is a use case

00:29:24.810 --> 00:29:26.400
that doesn't even violate our red lines.

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:29.340
We're worried that there will
be a hundred times as much,

00:29:29.340 --> 00:29:31.920
you know, with, with use cases that, that,

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:33.300
that do violate our red lines.

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:35.430
Now I, you know, I I I,
you know, again, again,

00:29:35.430 --> 00:29:39.420
I would say I think overall
the use of these, the, the use

00:29:39.420 --> 00:29:41.320
of these models is appropriate.

00:29:41.320 --> 00:29:43.660
I think it's good on net, you know,

00:29:43.660 --> 00:29:48.040
but military decision makers
make terrible mistakes even

00:29:48.040 --> 00:29:49.870
when, even, even at the best of times,

00:29:49.870 --> 00:29:51.910
and I, I don't know if
we're in the best of times.

00:29:51.910 --> 00:29:54.880
What we've seen here is Claude assists,

00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:56.410
but a human makes the final call.

00:29:56.410 --> 00:29:59.200
So a human made that
final call, not Claude.

00:29:59.200 --> 00:30:02.530
Imagine if you had a world
in which, not Claude,

00:30:02.530 --> 00:30:05.290
because we haven't allowed it,
but someone else's AI model,

00:30:05.290 --> 00:30:06.730
the AI model just makes the decision

00:30:06.730 --> 00:30:08.020
and the human never sees it.

00:30:08.020 --> 00:30:09.520
That's what we were standing up for.

00:30:09.520 --> 00:30:11.170
That's what we were fighting against.

00:30:11.170 --> 00:30:12.970
This school had a website.

00:30:12.970 --> 00:30:14.560
You could have found
it in a Google Search,

00:30:14.560 --> 00:30:16.600
like shouldn't Claude have spotted that?

00:30:16.600 --> 00:30:20.200
And it doesn't speak to a
scarier issue about using

00:30:20.200 --> 00:30:22.420
technology as a shortcut in war.

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:26.620
The principle that was obeyed
here is a human makes the

00:30:26.620 --> 00:30:28.420
human makes the final decision.

00:30:28.420 --> 00:30:31.600
I don't know what role
Claude or any other AI had,

00:30:31.600 --> 00:30:34.720
but like, if, if this
isn't an illustration why

00:30:34.720 --> 00:30:37.305
that principle is so important,
I don't know what is,

00:30:37.305 --> 00:30:40.900
Is AI warfare more likely

00:30:40.900 --> 00:30:45.670
to stop World War III, a war
between the US and China?

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:48.190
Or is it more likely to make it happen?

00:30:48.190 --> 00:30:50.650
I would say on balance it
is more likely to stop it.

00:30:50.650 --> 00:30:55.180
But if we have no limits on
how it's used, then I think,

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:56.980
you know, it could be
more likely to cause it.

00:30:56.980 --> 00:30:58.630
You've seen Dr. StrangeLove, right?

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:00.430
The premise of it was like, you know,

00:31:00.430 --> 00:31:01.780
you have a doomsday device

00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:04.090
that automatically fires
nuclear weapons when it thinks

00:31:04.090 --> 00:31:05.590
nuclear weapons are being fired at it.

00:31:05.590 --> 00:31:07.150
What could go wrong? Right?

00:31:07.150 --> 00:31:10.450
I think the way conflicts
happen is that, you know, the,

00:31:10.450 --> 00:31:11.830
the two sides jump at each other.

00:31:11.830 --> 00:31:13.420
They misunderstand each other.

00:31:13.420 --> 00:31:16.120
And when we don't have proper
oversight of this technology,

00:31:16.120 --> 00:31:19.420
I think those kinds of accidents
are more likely to happen.

00:31:19.420 --> 00:31:22.750
Now, I think if AI is used in
an appropriate way, in, in,

00:31:22.750 --> 00:31:24.250
in, not even warfare,

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:28.720
but think of just, just
intelligence collection, you know,

00:31:28.720 --> 00:31:31.810
let, let's say we're able to,
you know, predict an invasion

00:31:31.810 --> 00:31:34.330
of Taiwan or a new movement in Ukraine.

00:31:34.330 --> 00:31:38.860
Like, you know, our adversaries
will think twice about,

00:31:38.860 --> 00:31:41.500
you know, about conducting
some kind of invasion

00:31:41.500 --> 00:31:42.910
or military operation if we know

00:31:42.910 --> 00:31:43.960
everything that they're doing.

00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:49.360
AI's role on the battlefield
raises difficult questions,

00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:52.090
even for a company willing to
debate the ethical dilemmas

00:31:52.090 --> 00:31:53.890
of its own technology.

00:31:53.890 --> 00:31:57.160
It's a conversation Amodei seems
eager to have in public.

00:31:58.090 --> 00:32:00.190
How do you handle the pressure?

00:32:00.190 --> 00:32:02.770
I try very hard to communicate

00:32:02.770 --> 00:32:04.840
and always be straightforward and honest.

00:32:04.840 --> 00:32:08.140
I get up in front of the
company every two weeks

00:32:08.140 --> 00:32:11.260
and just talk for an hour
about just what's on my mind,

00:32:11.260 --> 00:32:12.370
what's going on in the industry,

00:32:12.370 --> 00:32:14.230
what's going on in the outside world.

00:32:14.230 --> 00:32:15.730
It's totally uncensored.

00:32:15.730 --> 00:32:19.120
And not only does it build
trust, it's very freeing for me

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:22.090
where I feel that I have 3,000 people

00:32:22.090 --> 00:32:23.860
who are on the same page as me.

00:32:23.860 --> 00:32:26.410
That is an incredible amplifier

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:28.450
and is one of the most useful things in

00:32:28.450 --> 00:32:29.980
handing, handling the pressure.

00:32:29.980 --> 00:32:33.460
Then when we have to confront
an external challenge,

00:32:33.460 --> 00:32:37.240
stand up to, you know, some
very difficult situations

00:32:37.240 --> 00:32:39.650
that we've seen in the
last few months, that is

00:32:39.650 --> 00:32:42.950
what allows us to have a
consistent and coherent position.

00:32:42.950 --> 00:32:45.680
And, and I think, I think
it's an incredible advantage

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:47.270
because I never feel like I'm alone.

00:32:54.020 --> 00:32:56.510
Lurking in the background
at Anthropic's headquarters was

00:32:56.510 --> 00:32:59.660
the surprise development of
a new AI model called Mythos.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.470
A model so powerful, it spooked everyone.

00:33:04.550 --> 00:33:06.650
Anthropic is making headlines
almost on a weekly basis.

00:33:06.650 --> 00:33:08.450
Yes,
Most notably now around mythos.

00:33:08.450 --> 00:33:11.630
The company believes
it's this enormous threat.

00:33:11.630 --> 00:33:13.760
Imagine a world where
everyone had a nuclear

00:33:13.760 --> 00:33:15.470
bazooka basically

00:33:15.470 --> 00:33:16.970
Mythos identified thousands

00:33:16.970 --> 00:33:18.860
of cybersecurity vulnerabilities,

00:33:18.860 --> 00:33:22.970
exposing potential flaws in
every major operating system.

00:33:22.970 --> 00:33:26.210
Anthropic signaled that if
fully released mythos could hack

00:33:26.210 --> 00:33:28.550
banks, pry open state secrets

00:33:28.550 --> 00:33:30.260
and cripple critical infrastructure.

00:33:31.310 --> 00:33:35.720
I think the thing that
surprised me most about it was the

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:38.240
models had been climbing in their ability

00:33:38.240 --> 00:33:39.560
to find vulnerabilities.

00:33:39.560 --> 00:33:41.330
It was a particularly large jump.

00:33:41.330 --> 00:33:43.640
Some of the early
companies that we gave this

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:47.030
to said things like, this is a
super weapon, you should have

00:33:47.030 --> 00:33:49.310
to own a gun license to use it.

00:33:49.310 --> 00:33:51.230
Please don't release this. In

00:33:52.370 --> 00:33:54.230
an initiative called Project Glasswing,

00:33:54.230 --> 00:33:57.560
Anthropic gave select
organizations access to Mythos.

00:33:58.490 --> 00:34:00.950
Even federal agencies
like the National Security

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:02.090
Administration clamored

00:34:02.090 --> 00:34:05.180
to use it despite Anthropic's
blacklisting by the Pentagon.

00:34:06.050 --> 00:34:08.270
I think the future is this kind of cat

00:34:08.270 --> 00:34:11.210
and mouse game where we need to make sure

00:34:11.210 --> 00:34:15.230
that the good guys have the
tools that they need to defend,

00:34:15.230 --> 00:34:16.970
and then at some point the, you know,

00:34:16.970 --> 00:34:18.020
the bad guys will have it too.

00:34:18.020 --> 00:34:19.520
And, and at that point we have

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:21.770
to make sure the good guys
have an even better model

00:34:21.770 --> 00:34:23.270
so they can be ready for this.

00:34:23.270 --> 00:34:24.950
Is it possible to stay ahead

00:34:24.950 --> 00:34:26.780
of the bad guys really though?

00:34:26.780 --> 00:34:29.450
That's what we hope
the criticism is.

00:34:29.450 --> 00:34:32.570
You're effectively deciding who
gets access and who doesn't.

00:34:32.570 --> 00:34:34.520
Why should anyone be
comfortable with that kind

00:34:34.520 --> 00:34:36.860
of concentration of power?

00:34:36.860 --> 00:34:38.390
It wasn't like, oh, it's so powerful

00:34:38.390 --> 00:34:40.580
and let's decide who gets the power.

00:34:40.580 --> 00:34:44.450
It was a very specific
concern around cybersecurity

00:34:44.450 --> 00:34:47.480
and so the way that we
decided who to give the model

00:34:47.480 --> 00:34:49.760
to was grounded in that specific fear.

00:34:49.760 --> 00:34:51.350
There's obviously nuance to decide, like

00:34:51.350 --> 00:34:53.090
where do you draw that circle?

00:34:53.090 --> 00:34:54.500
I think that's really complicated.

00:34:54.500 --> 00:34:58.220
I think we've tried to be
as publicly open as possible

00:34:58.220 --> 00:35:00.770
to say we're trying our best
to make this decision well,

00:35:00.770 --> 00:35:03.380
but like we might not do it perfectly.

00:35:03.380 --> 00:35:05.780
What about the folks who say
this was just good marketing.

00:35:06.710 --> 00:35:10.100
You know, we, we have
suffered enormously commercially

00:35:10.100 --> 00:35:11.630
from not releasing this model.

00:35:11.630 --> 00:35:15.140
This model has incredibly
accelerated research within

00:35:15.140 --> 00:35:17.960
Anthropic and production and next models.

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:20.120
It would do the same in
the outside world if,

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:21.530
if we were to release it.

00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:24.440
This has hurt us enormously commercially.

00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:25.970
Have you had to make trade-offs already

00:35:25.970 --> 00:35:27.920
that you're not entirely comfortable with?

00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:29.690
Throughout the entire history

00:35:29.690 --> 00:35:32.180
of Anthropic has been trade-offs, right?

00:35:32.180 --> 00:35:34.370
In some ideal world, you would prefer to,

00:35:34.370 --> 00:35:36.680
before you release the
first chat bot, you know,

00:35:36.680 --> 00:35:39.150
you could spend years
studying, you know, every,

00:35:39.150 --> 00:35:41.280
every possible thing that
could go wrong with it.

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:44.250
Now, we did delay, we did
delay the initial release

00:35:44.250 --> 00:35:46.620
of Claude, but you know,
we did it for a few months.

00:35:46.620 --> 00:35:51.120
So everything is a trade off
now that we're in, you know,

00:35:51.120 --> 00:35:54.180
what I would describe as a
commercially leading position,

00:35:54.180 --> 00:35:56.550
we can afford to move
the dial even further

00:35:56.550 --> 00:35:57.900
towards being careful, right?

00:35:57.900 --> 00:36:00.030
That's what the Mythos
release was about, right?

00:36:00.030 --> 00:36:01.560
It's very hard to do something like

00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:04.080
that if you're not the leading player.

00:36:04.080 --> 00:36:06.660
There's this argument, why wouldn't the

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:07.890
government take you over?

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:10.800
Why would they let a
private company control

00:36:10.800 --> 00:36:12.510
technology? That's so powerful?

00:36:12.510 --> 00:36:15.000
So I think, I actually
think that's a very,

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:18.360
that's a very serious question
and I share those concerns.

00:36:18.360 --> 00:36:21.000
I don't think the government
should outright take us over.

00:36:22.260 --> 00:36:26.820
Every previous powerful technology
we've seen in history was

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:28.140
either built by the government

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:29.670
or originated with the government.

00:36:29.670 --> 00:36:33.180
So nuclear weapons, obviously,
you know, initially built

00:36:33.180 --> 00:36:37.380
by the government, the
internet, GPS, cell phones,

00:36:37.380 --> 00:36:38.970
AI is the first technology

00:36:38.970 --> 00:36:40.830
that's been built in the private sector

00:36:41.700 --> 00:36:44.550
and where government has not
really had a serious role

00:36:44.550 --> 00:36:46.650
and is coming in late to the game.

00:36:46.650 --> 00:36:49.830
I think that's actually a
dangerous and unstable situation.

00:36:49.830 --> 00:36:53.370
It is not the situation I
would've chosen this technology.

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:54.810
I'm scared of companies having it,

00:36:54.810 --> 00:36:56.910
but I'm also scared of
government having it.

00:36:56.910 --> 00:36:58.020
And then, you know,

00:36:58.020 --> 00:37:00.690
we need basic regulation
of the technology.

00:37:00.690 --> 00:37:01.830
You know, more

00:37:01.830 --> 00:37:04.710
and more as I've seen what we've
seen with Mythos, you know,

00:37:04.710 --> 00:37:07.530
I think we need to start
doing pre-release testing,

00:37:07.530 --> 00:37:09.900
required pre-release testing, testing

00:37:09.900 --> 00:37:11.730
and auditing of the models.

00:37:11.730 --> 00:37:13.680
And this was an approach
the White House rejected

00:37:13.680 --> 00:37:17.430
initially on his first day
back in office, President Trump

00:37:17.430 --> 00:37:18.750
with the help of former AI

00:37:18.750 --> 00:37:22.560
and crypto czar, David Sachs
dismantled President Biden's AI

00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:24.810
executive order seeking guardrails,

00:37:24.810 --> 00:37:26.640
instead favoring a hands-off,

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:29.460
let Silicon Valley do its thing approach.

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:31.800
We believe that excessive regulation

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:36.330
of the AI sector could kill a
transformative industry just

00:37:36.330 --> 00:37:38.100
as it's taking off.

00:37:38.100 --> 00:37:40.740
But with Mythos and its
national security implications,

00:37:40.740 --> 00:37:44.160
proving hard to ignore the
White House now seems to want

00:37:44.160 --> 00:37:46.620
to gatekeep the world's most powerful ai

00:37:47.910 --> 00:37:51.120
It's very funny to me how
there's a particular group

00:37:51.120 --> 00:37:54.120
of people in the tech world in
Silicon Valley, they started

00:37:54.120 --> 00:37:57.930
with a position of like, you
know, even having transparency

00:37:57.930 --> 00:38:00.450
around this technology, even
export control, you know,

00:38:00.450 --> 00:38:02.790
this is all, you know, just totally,

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:05.520
it'll apocalyptically
destroy our potential

00:38:05.520 --> 00:38:06.720
to create the technology.

00:38:06.720 --> 00:38:08.520
It'll kill innovation.

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:10.650
And then as soon as they
see the first real danger,

00:38:10.650 --> 00:38:13.140
which I've been expecting all
along, there's all this talk

00:38:13.140 --> 00:38:14.250
of like nationalization

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:15.990
and the government should just seize it.

00:38:15.990 --> 00:38:17.340
Come on folks here, you're yo,

00:38:17.340 --> 00:38:22.080
you're yo-yoing from like the
most extreme anti-regulatory.

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:23.490
If you look at us the wrong way,

00:38:23.490 --> 00:38:25.350
you're destroying the
industry to, you know,

00:38:25.350 --> 00:38:26.880
this completely communist,

00:38:26.880 --> 00:38:28.560
the government should grab it all.

00:38:28.560 --> 00:38:30.930
We, we need, we, we need a more,

00:38:30.930 --> 00:38:33.060
we need a more sensible,
moderate approach.

00:38:33.060 --> 00:38:35.110
That's the one we've
been favoring all along

00:38:35.110 --> 00:38:36.880
because we've, we've understood the

00:38:36.880 --> 00:38:38.320
power of this technology.

00:38:38.320 --> 00:38:41.170
We're not panicking, we're not denying it.

00:38:41.170 --> 00:38:42.760
We see the smooth exponential

00:38:42.760 --> 00:38:44.410
and we're responding to it appropriately.

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:56.170
The reaction to AI
right now, it's intense.

00:38:56.170 --> 00:38:59.020
Anthropic has built this
really loyal following.

00:38:59.020 --> 00:39:01.720
There are some people who
just love what they stand for,

00:39:01.720 --> 00:39:05.050
but there've also been protests
right outside their office.

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:07.900
There's a lot of anxiety,
a lot of confusion,

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:12.700
there's some real anger right
now about what's happening

00:39:12.700 --> 00:39:15.130
and it actually feels
like it's escalating.

00:39:15.130 --> 00:39:18.520
Artificial intelligence is

00:39:18.520 --> 00:39:20.530
the next industrial revolution. Whoa.

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:27.400
If you look at the data,

00:39:27.400 --> 00:39:29.410
people are more concerned than excited

00:39:29.410 --> 00:39:31.210
about what's going on.

00:39:31.210 --> 00:39:33.430
They think the risks outweigh the benefits

00:39:33.430 --> 00:39:35.800
and the truth is, if
you talk to the people

00:39:35.800 --> 00:39:37.180
who are building this,

00:39:37.180 --> 00:39:40.090
even they will tell you
they don't fully know

00:39:40.090 --> 00:39:41.320
how it's all going to play out.

00:39:45.160 --> 00:39:47.950
How do you think about
the weight of this moment?

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:50.560
I worry that something will go wrong.

00:39:50.560 --> 00:39:52.510
You know, are we doing
literally everything we can?

00:39:52.510 --> 00:39:54.130
We're certainly trying our best,

00:39:54.130 --> 00:39:55.990
we're certainly trying very hard.

00:39:55.990 --> 00:39:58.300
What I want is to create a
situation where if this set

00:39:58.300 --> 00:40:00.280
of people can't do it,
it couldn't be done.

00:40:00.280 --> 00:40:01.480
You can't guarantee success,

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:02.740
but maybe you can guarantee that

00:40:04.030 --> 00:40:05.500
It's getting personal.

00:40:05.500 --> 00:40:08.500
Sam Altman's home has been attacked.

00:40:08.500 --> 00:40:10.240
How is that affecting you?

00:40:10.240 --> 00:40:11.800
It was really scary to read that.

00:40:11.800 --> 00:40:15.580
I mean, it was, we were obviously
extremely relieved that he

00:40:15.580 --> 00:40:17.560
and his family were okay in general.

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:20.080
I think this is a time,
you know, technologically,

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:23.830
politically where unfortunately
there's just a lot more

00:40:23.830 --> 00:40:26.830
rhetoric and, and words
that I think can lead to,

00:40:26.830 --> 00:40:29.680
to bad outcomes and bad things happening.

00:40:29.680 --> 00:40:31.660
I hope that this is a topic
we can all just debate,

00:40:31.660 --> 00:40:34.090
you know, as peacefully as possible.

00:40:34.090 --> 00:40:35.200
It was scary to me too.

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:38.320
I mean, you know, this is
like a, a less savory aspect

00:40:38.320 --> 00:40:39.340
of the exponential, right?

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:41.500
That as AI gets more

00:40:41.500 --> 00:40:43.540
and more of, of a big
thing like, you know,

00:40:43.540 --> 00:40:46.870
it becomes just such
a big deal to society.

00:40:46.870 --> 00:40:48.400
There's more attention on it.

00:40:48.400 --> 00:40:51.430
There's been massive
backlash against social media.

00:40:51.430 --> 00:40:54.550
Countries are starting to ban
it. Could that happen to AI?

00:40:55.960 --> 00:40:58.180
I think it's, it's absolutely possible.

00:40:58.180 --> 00:41:00.700
If the social media companies
could go back in time

00:41:00.700 --> 00:41:02.590
and see the world that they see today,

00:41:02.590 --> 00:41:04.660
would they do anything differently?

00:41:04.660 --> 00:41:06.070
I like to think the answer to that is yes.

00:41:06.070 --> 00:41:09.760
I don't know if we sort of
project some of the challenges

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:11.680
that the social media companies have faced

00:41:11.680 --> 00:41:15.610
around child welfare, mental
health, election integrity, all

00:41:15.610 --> 00:41:19.180
of these topics we're really
lucky that we're we're second.

00:41:19.180 --> 00:41:20.800
We view it as our job to try

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:22.390
and proactively think about all

00:41:22.390 --> 00:41:24.220
of the things that could go wrong.

00:41:24.220 --> 00:41:25.930
Because if we don't, who's going to,

00:41:25.930 --> 00:41:28.360
You know, I don't know
that they actually set out

00:41:28.360 --> 00:41:30.790
to do the right thing or make
the world a better place.

00:41:30.790 --> 00:41:33.020
And so I don't think if
they were going back,

00:41:33.020 --> 00:41:34.580
they would even knowing what they do,

00:41:34.580 --> 00:41:36.770
and they certainly should
do things differently.

00:41:36.770 --> 00:41:39.290
I don't know if they
actually will, but we can't.

00:41:39.290 --> 00:41:40.520
This is why we're trying

00:41:40.520 --> 00:41:43.130
to get this right the first
time instead of waiting

00:41:43.130 --> 00:41:46.400
for things to go wrong, then scrambling

00:41:46.400 --> 00:41:48.290
to justify why it's all okay.

00:41:48.290 --> 00:41:52.310
The main way I could see a
AI being, you know, banned

00:41:52.310 --> 00:41:54.470
or blocked is if something
really went wrong

00:41:54.470 --> 00:41:55.550
and if something really went wrong,

00:41:55.550 --> 00:41:56.930
then maybe it deserves to be,

00:41:56.930 --> 00:42:00.230
You have technologists
saying it's gonna be amazing

00:42:00.230 --> 00:42:02.090
and others saying it could be awful.

00:42:02.090 --> 00:42:04.700
Where are you on that spectrum?

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:07.400
I hope for the best,
but plan for the worst.

00:42:07.400 --> 00:42:10.250
For me, this is the most
important work I've ever done.

00:42:10.250 --> 00:42:13.070
For some people it feels
like this is the last job

00:42:13.070 --> 00:42:16.460
because this is sort of the,
it could mean the end of work

00:42:16.460 --> 00:42:18.740
and I think for other
people it's, you know,

00:42:18.740 --> 00:42:20.630
like maybe it's not the last job,

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:23.540
but it's existential to get this right.

00:42:23.540 --> 00:42:25.760
And so there's just this,
this kind of burden.

00:42:25.760 --> 00:42:28.880
If the impacts could be as significant

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:30.740
as we're talking about, as significant

00:42:30.740 --> 00:42:32.780
as Anthropic has warned about,

00:42:32.780 --> 00:42:35.510
what responsibility do
you think Anthropic has

00:42:35.510 --> 00:42:37.340
to cushion the blow?

00:42:37.340 --> 00:42:41.810
What do you owe the people
whose lives you've upended?

00:42:43.130 --> 00:42:45.830
I think our view has always been,

00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:48.650
we ultimately are responsible
as an industry, the industry

00:42:48.650 --> 00:42:52.940
that's developing this technology
for thinking through what

00:42:52.940 --> 00:42:55.940
are the risks, what are the
bad things that could happen?

00:42:55.940 --> 00:42:57.740
And if some of those things come to pass,

00:42:57.740 --> 00:42:59.900
what is our role in helping to fix them?

00:42:59.900 --> 00:43:01.580
That is our job, right?

00:43:01.580 --> 00:43:03.860
We should not just say,
well, we were just trying

00:43:03.860 --> 00:43:05.750
to grow the product and
suddenly there's an entire

00:43:05.750 --> 00:43:09.350
generation of young women
who have eating disorders

00:43:09.350 --> 00:43:11.060
or who have mental health problems

00:43:11.060 --> 00:43:13.250
because whoops, we were just
trying to grow the product.

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:14.360
That's not the stance

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:16.220
that I think any technology
company should take.

00:43:16.220 --> 00:43:17.960
I don't think that's the stance
that we're trying to take

00:43:19.820 --> 00:43:22.550
For a company whose
identity is so wrapped up in,

00:43:22.550 --> 00:43:23.570
We want to do this right,

00:43:23.570 --> 00:43:25.550
We exist as a AI safety company.

00:43:25.550 --> 00:43:27.920
How can we just help
all of this go? Well,

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:30.440
It can be hard to understand
why Anthropic is pushing

00:43:30.440 --> 00:43:32.900
so hard to advance AI while being

00:43:32.900 --> 00:43:36.350
so upfront about the
dangers. In his essays,

00:43:36.350 --> 00:43:39.050
Dario lays out what the end
game looks like if everything

00:43:39.050 --> 00:43:42.260
goes right with ai, a
utopian future where machines

00:43:42.260 --> 00:43:45.500
and humans work side by side AI,

00:43:45.500 --> 00:43:48.740
an inevitable force steered
toward prosperity rather than

00:43:48.740 --> 00:43:53.180
catastrophe to mitigate the
devastation of job loss.

00:43:53.180 --> 00:43:56.300
He proposes solutions like
universal basic income

00:43:56.300 --> 00:43:58.820
and progressive taxation of AI companies.

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:03.980
But as the Amodeis confront the
messy realities of power,

00:44:03.980 --> 00:44:06.590
politics, and profit,
the real test is whether

00:44:06.590 --> 00:44:08.240
that founding mission can survive the

00:44:08.240 --> 00:44:09.800
scale of what they're building.

00:44:11.390 --> 00:44:14.090
Google started with the
motto, don't be evil.

00:44:14.090 --> 00:44:17.240
A founding promise the company
quietly retired as it grew.

00:44:19.610 --> 00:44:22.250
You are building something
incredibly powerful

00:44:22.250 --> 00:44:25.280
and stand to gain enormously from it.

00:44:25.280 --> 00:44:26.960
Why should we trust you?

00:44:26.960 --> 00:44:29.960
I think starting from a
position of distrust, you know,

00:44:29.960 --> 00:44:31.170
if you don't know anything about,

00:44:31.170 --> 00:44:32.003
if you don't know anything about

00:44:32.003 --> 00:44:33.510
philanthropic, it's pretty rational.

00:44:33.510 --> 00:44:36.570
I think Silicon Valley has
lost a lot of the world's trust

00:44:36.570 --> 00:44:38.460
and kind of has to re-earn it,

00:44:38.460 --> 00:44:41.340
and the message, you know,
we're trying to send is,

00:44:41.340 --> 00:44:42.900
we're actually different and,

00:44:42.900 --> 00:44:46.020
and that has to be earned in
things that we actually do.

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:48.210
I understand one of your
favorite books is The Making

00:44:48.210 --> 00:44:49.470
of the Atomic Bomb.

00:44:49.470 --> 00:44:51.180
That is correct.
Do you see parallels

00:44:51.180 --> 00:44:52.980
between yourself and Oppenheimer?

00:44:52.980 --> 00:44:56.010
The figure I most identified
with was Leo Szilard

00:44:56.010 --> 00:44:58.440
who was the one who first had the idea

00:44:58.440 --> 00:45:00.390
that there could be a chain reaction.

00:45:01.380 --> 00:45:04.080
Look, my view is we're, we're
not gonna get through this

00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:06.240
with like larger than life personalities

00:45:06.240 --> 00:45:09.990
or like figures who try and be
at the center of everything.

00:45:09.990 --> 00:45:13.020
In some ways, I actually see
Oppenheimer as a failure case, as

00:45:13.020 --> 00:45:14.550
what should not happen.

00:45:14.550 --> 00:45:17.850
There's a lot of powerful
actors who have interests here,

00:45:17.850 --> 00:45:19.620
and the only way it's gonna end well

00:45:19.620 --> 00:45:23.160
for everyone is if there is
some, there's basically checks

00:45:23.160 --> 00:45:24.810
and balances everywhere.

00:45:24.810 --> 00:45:28.380
You've said there's
roughly a 10 to 25% chance

00:45:28.380 --> 00:45:33.000
of civilization collapse,
that is not insignificant.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:35.730
Is there a scenario where it's something

00:45:35.730 --> 00:45:38.910
that Anthropic built, that caused that?

00:45:38.910 --> 00:45:40.410
I mean, I certainly hope not.

00:45:40.410 --> 00:45:44.790
My view is that that
probability comes from the very

00:45:44.790 --> 00:45:47.370
straightforward recipe of
the technology, the existence

00:45:47.370 --> 00:45:49.170
of many countries in the world.

00:45:49.170 --> 00:45:51.990
The existence of many
companies within an economy

00:45:51.990 --> 00:45:53.070
and new ones created.

00:45:53.070 --> 00:45:56.220
If the void is isn't filled,
like that's a dilemma

00:45:56.220 --> 00:45:59.310
that we're in half of what we
do within the company is try

00:45:59.310 --> 00:46:01.860
and, you know, reduce the
risk as much as we can,

00:46:01.860 --> 00:46:03.630
but it's never gonna be zero.

00:46:03.630 --> 00:46:05.010
Suppose there are a bunch of, you know,

00:46:05.010 --> 00:46:06.300
airline companies out there

00:46:06.300 --> 00:46:07.470
and you're like, well, I'm gonna make an

00:46:07.470 --> 00:46:08.820
airline company that's safer.

00:46:08.820 --> 00:46:11.130
It can both be the case that, you know,

00:46:11.130 --> 00:46:13.800
your airline company is 10
times safer than all the other

00:46:13.800 --> 00:46:15.060
airline companies.

00:46:15.060 --> 00:46:16.560
But if someone comes

00:46:16.560 --> 00:46:18.270
and asks you, like, can you guarantee

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:20.430
that your airplane will never crash?

00:46:20.430 --> 00:46:22.770
I mean, how could you,
how could you possibly,

00:46:22.770 --> 00:46:25.410
But if there was a 25%
chance of an airplane crashing,

00:46:25.410 --> 00:46:26.820
you wouldn't get on that plane.

00:46:26.820 --> 00:46:28.500
That's right. 25% is too high.

